# **Angular component structure** 

      1\.  **Angular Component Structure**

Each Angular component typically has three main files:

* **`.ts`** : Contains the component logic (class, variables, methods).  
* **`.html`**: Defines the component template (UI structure).  
* **`.css` :** Styles the component (can be replaced by Tailwind classes)

       2\.   **Separation of Concerns**

Angular promotes separation of concerns:

* **Logic**: In `.ts` — handles data, events, and business logic.  
* **Template**: In `.html` — handles how data is displayed.  
* **Style**: In `.css` — handles how the component looks.

# **Module management** 

1. **What is an Angular model ?**

Modules are containers that group components, directives, pipes, and services.

![][image4]

2. **Root Module vs Feature Modules**

	**Root module is :**

* The main entry point of any Angular application.  
* It's the module that Angular loads first when the app starts.  
* Typically named `AppModule` and located in [`app.module.ts`](http://app.module.ts) `.`  
* Bootstraps the application using the root component (usually `AppComponent`).

	**Feature modules are :**

* represent a feature or section of your application ( Users, Admin, Products).  
* Can be lazy-loaded to improve performance (loading a module only when it’s needed) .  
* Help organize the app and make it scalable and maintainable, instead of putting everything into one big module,  you split your app into smaller parts.

3. **Standalone Components** 

   Normally in Angular, every component must be declared inside an NgModule (like `AppModule` or a feature module).

   But with Standalone Components, you don’t need a module anymore. You can create a component that works on its own.

   ![][image5]

   Use cases : 

For small apps, For lazy-loaded routes, When creating reusable components like 

buttons.

# **Services and API calls** 

	A service is a separate file (a TypeScript class) where we write things like:  API calls 

	(get users, add products, etc.), business logic (calculations, filters, etc.), reusable

code.  
	And then we just inject that service in the component to use it.

# **Model definitions** 

A model is a TypeScript interface or class that defines the structure of the  

data you're working with in your app.

To define a ts model there is two options:

**Option A: Using an `interface`**

export interface User {

  id: number;

  name: string;

  email: string; }

 **Option B: Using a `class`**

export class User {

  constructor(

    public id: number,

    public name: string,

    public email: string  ) {}}

	The main role of an angular model is data type checking and safety with APIs .

 **Models in an Angular App:**

First you need to define the model, expl: 

export interface User {

  id: number;

  name: string;

  email: string; }

Second,  use it in the service: 

import { HttpClient } from '@angular/common/http';

import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';

import { Observable } from 'rxjs';

import { User } from './user.model';  // Import model

@Injectable({

  providedIn: 'root'})

export class UserService {

  private apiUrl \= 'https://api.example.com/users';

  constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}

  getUsers(): Observable\<User\[\]\> {

    return this.http.get\<User\[\]\>(this.apiUrl);  }}

Third use it in the component:

import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';

import { UserService } from './user.service';

import { User } from './user.model';  // Import model

@Component({

  selector: 'app-user-list',

  template: \`

    \<ul\>\<li \*ngFor="let user of users"\> {{ user.name }} \- {{ user.email }}  \</li\>  \</ul\>

  \`})

export class UserListComponent implements OnInit {

  users: User\[\] \= \[\];

  constructor(private userService: UserService) {}

  ngOnInit(): void {

    this.userService.getUsers().subscribe(data \=\> {

      this.users \= data;  }); }}

# **Tailwind CSS integration** 

	Install Tailwind CSS in Angular: npm install \-D tailwindcss postcss autoprefixer

	Then initialize Tailwind:  npx tailwindcss init

	Configure Tailwind : In your `tailwind.config.js`, update the content array to 

	scan your Angular files by adding this line :    content: \["./src/\*\*/\*.{html,ts}",  \],

	Add Tailwind to Angular styles: 

@tailwind base;

@tailwind components;

@tailwind utilities;
